{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17533677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17533677"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:38:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:38:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14858"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14858"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.15,0.07,0.04,0.72]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7549"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59055"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7549"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14858"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44466"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1027"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3161"},{"type":"tags","id":"11691"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18467"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59055","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59055"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for review of her depression. She has a history of obsessive-compulsive personality disorder and takes sertraline 100 mg daily. When asked about her mood, she begins by describing her morning routine in extensive detail, including what she had for breakfast, the weather, her commute to work, interactions with colleagues, and various work tasks, before eventually stating that she has been feeling low for the past two weeks. This pattern continues throughout the consultation. She does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her affect is restricted but appropriate. There is no evidence of psychotic symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes her thought pattern?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thought blocking","Tangential thinking","Flight of ideas","Loosening of associations","Circumferential thinking"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient demonstrates \u003Cstrong\u003Ecircumferential thinking\u003C/strong\u003E (also called circumstantial thinking), which is characterised by indirect, over-inclusive speech that eventually reaches its intended point. The patient includes excessive detail and numerous peripheral details before arriving at the core message about her mood symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETangential thinking\u003C/strong\u003E differs from circumferential thinking in that the patient never returns to the original point or answers the question posed. Instead, they move from one topic to another without reaching a conclusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlight of ideas\u003C/strong\u003E involves rapid shifting between topics with connections based on rhyming, puns, or other associations. It is typically seen in mania and differs from this patient\u0027s methodical, albeit detailed, progression through related topics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELoosening of associations\u003C/strong\u003E is a more severe thought disorder where connections between ideas are illogical or absent. It is typically seen in schizophrenia and other psychotic disorders, which this patient does not demonstrate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThought blocking\u003C/strong\u003E refers to an abrupt interruption in the flow of thinking and speech, where the patient suddenly stops mid-sentence and cannot continue their train of thought. This pattern is not described in the stem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECircumferential thinking is commonly seen in obsessive-compulsive personality disorder, as these individuals often have difficulty distinguishing essential from non-essential details and feel compelled to include all information they consider relevant.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Circumferential thinking is characterised by indirect, over-inclusive speech that takes a long time to reach its point","Circumferential thinking differs from tangential thinking in that the patient eventually reaches their point","Circumferential speech is commonly seen in obsessive-compulsive personality disorder"],"references":["Voss R, Das J. Mental status examination. StatPearls. 2024 Apr 30."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44466"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14858"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44466"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-04T14:45:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-04T14:47:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7549"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59055"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonym